259 //
260 // Define query system time macro.
261 //
262 // The following AMD64 code reads an unaligned quadword value. The quadword
263 // value, however, is guaranteed to be within a cache line, and therefore,
264 // the value will be read atomically.
265 //
266 
267 #if defined(_AMD64_)
268 
269 #define KiQuerySystemTime(CurrentTime) \
270  (CurrentTime)->QuadPart = *((LONG64 volatile *)(&SharedUserData->SystemTime))
271 
272 #else
273 
274 #define KiQuerySystemTime(CurrentTime) \
275  while (TRUE) { \
276  (CurrentTime)->HighPart = SharedUserData->SystemTime.High1Time; \
277  (CurrentTime)->LowPart = SharedUserData->SystemTime.LowPart; \
278  if ((CurrentTime)->HighPart == SharedUserData->SystemTime.High2Time) break; \
279  PAUSE_PROCESSOR \
280  }
281 
282 #endif
283 
284 #if defined(_AMD64_)
285 
286 #define KiQueryLowTickCount() SharedUserData->TickCount.LowPart
287 
288 #else
289 
290 #define KiQueryLowTickCount() KeTickCount.LowPart
291 
292 #endif

295 // Enumerated kernel types
296 //
297 // Kernel object types.
298 //
299 // N.B. There are really two types of event objects; NotificationEvent and
300 // SynchronizationEvent. The type value for a notification event is 0,
301 // and that for a synchronization event 1.
302 //
303 // N.B. There are two types of new timer objects; NotificationTimer and
304 // SynchronizationTimer. The type value for a notification timer is
305 // 8, and that for a synchronization timer is 9. These values are
306 // very carefully chosen so that the dispatcher object type AND'ed
307 // with 0x7 yields 0 or 1 for event objects and the timer objects.
308 //
309 
310 #define DISPATCHER_OBJECT_TYPE_MASK 0x7
